            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Bambu Lab</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://us.store.bambulab.com/products/p1p"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Even as 3D printing gets more accessible, it can still be painfully slow. But Bambu’s P1P has streamlined both the speed and quality of the process. The P1P is ready to print in just about 15 minutes after taking it out of the box, which is refreshing compared to some models that take hours. Once it’s running, the P1P can print at a rate of up to 500 millimeters per second (mm/s), which is nearly twice what printers at this price typically output. Plus, the head accelerates at an impressive 20,000 mm/s². Despite its speed, this machine spits out objects that are smooth, detailed, and free from errors. Bonus: It costs less than $1,000.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-mx2a-by-cherry-a-classic-mechanical-keyboard-switch-gets-a-high-tech-makeover">MX2A by Cherry: A classic mechanical keyboard switch gets a high-tech makeover</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.cherrymx.de/en/mx2a.html" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/cherry-mx2a-switch-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Cherry</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.cherrymx.de/en/mx2a.html"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>You probably never think about it, but every time you press a key on your keyboard, you’re activating a switch. The original Cherry MX keyboard switches hit the market in 1983, winning the hearts of nerds everywhere with their impeccable feel and clacky sound. The MX2A redefines those classic switches for an even better feel and longevity beyond the 100 million strokes promised by the originals. Cherry developed a new proprietary lubrication mix and technique for applying the slippery stuff to the socket dome in the key’s rear housing. Along with a stronger barrel-shaped spring (instead of a typical cylinder), six ribs that keep the key centered, and redesigned socket geometry, these upgrades create the bounciest, clickiest keys yet.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-quest-3-by-meta-accessible-mixed-reality-for-the-real-and-virtual-world">Quest 3 by Meta: Accessible mixed reality for the real (and virtual) world</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.meta.com/quest/quest-3/" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/meta-quest-3-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Meta</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.meta.com/quest/quest-3/"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Years ago, a company called <a href="https://www.popsci.com/2017-year-tech/">Magic Leap</a> promised immersive mixed reality (MR) that blended digital objects with the real world at a consumer level. It worked, but it wasn’t practical enough to catch on thanks to its clunky hardware and clumsy images. The Meta Quest 3, however, delivers that promised MR experience in an accessible way. A pair of cameras and a depth sensor dutifully recreate the real world in the headset’s 4K+ infinite display. Digital objects seamlessly blend into the terrain so convincingly that taking off the headset can feel slightly disorienting—it’s a truly impressive experience from a standalone headset.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-deep-dark-technology-by-unistellar-a-chance-for-city-dwellers-to-see-the-stars">Deep Dark Technology by Unistellar: A chance for city dwellers to see the stars</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.unistellar.com/deep-dark-technology/" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Unisteller-eVscope-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Unistellar</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.unistellar.com/deep-dark-technology/"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Light pollution makes stargazing all but impossible in many urban areas, but Unistellar built a solution for that view-ruining haze. The company has analyzed millions of images captured by its smart telescopes to collect a comprehensive view of the night sky. Its Deep Dark tech assesses the scene a telescope user is looking at, recognizing which objects belong there and which are simply products of light pollution. The result? A clear, detailed map of deep space objects that would otherwise be impossible in a well-lit area.&nbsp;</p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading has-text-align-center" id="aerospace" style="font-style:normal;font-weight:700">Aerospace</h2>



<p>It’s been an exciting year in the aerospace industry. Two heavyweights—NASA and Boeing—announced that they were teaming up to create a new research aircraft called the <a href="https://www.popsci.com/technology/nasa-x-planes/">X-66A</a>, also known as the <a href="https://www.popsci.com/technology/nasa-boeing-announce-sustainable-flight-demonstrator/">Sustainable Flight Demonstrator</a>. The goal of the program is to make an experimental passenger aircraft that will be more efficient with the fuel it consumes. And speaking of sustainability, two different companies working on electric aircraft—Joby Aviation and Beta Technologies—delivered battery-powered flying machines to the Air Force for testing. What’s more, Alaska Airlines <a target="_blank" href="https://news.alaskaair.com/alaska-airlines/alaska-airlines-and-stumptown-new-coffee/">claims to have concocted</a> a coffee blend that it says tastes good up at high altitudes. (What will they think of next?) But the biggest breakthroughs of the past 12 months include a giant rocket, exciting new space exploration missions, and a sixth-generation bomber for the Air Force. Take a look.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-grand-award-winner-aerospace">Grand Award Winner, Aerospace</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-juice-by-the-european-space-agency-esa-on-a-quest-for-hidden-seas">JUICE by the European Space Agency (ESA): On a quest for hidden seas</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Space_Science/Juice" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/JUICE-FNL-2.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>ESA</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Space_Science/Juice"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Science fiction has long abounded with tales of life teeming in subsurface oceans on worlds like Europa, an ice-coated moon of Jupiter. Soon, we’ll have a close look at Europa and other Jovian moons, thanks to ESA’s Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE), which launched on April 14 this year. JUICE’s science instruments include spectrographs and penetrating radar designed specifically to peer under ice, making it primed to explore not just Europa, but also its fellow icebound moons Ganymede and Callisto. JUICE will arrive at Jupiter in 2031 and, after orbiting the gas giant for more than three years, will move itself into Ganymede’s orbit in 2034 for further study.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-psyche-by-nasa-jpl-and-arizona-state-university-to-deep-space-without-rocket-fuel">Psyche by NASA/JPL and Arizona State University: To deep space without rocket fuel</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://psyche.asu.edu/" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/psyche_FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>NASA</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://psyche.asu.edu/"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>NASA’s <em>Psyche </em>is flying through space thanks to a futuristic propulsion system. <em>Psyche </em>isn’t like traditional space probes that rely on thrust from dramatic chemical reactions. Instead, itrelies on solar power, which produces electricity that strips xenon atoms into ions and pushes them out the back. This type of propulsion has propelled spacecraft before, but <em>Psyche </em>uses a type called a Hall-effect thruster; <em>Psyche</em>’s engine relies on a magnetic field to corral the xenon ions, boosting the thruster’s efficiency. In fact, <em>Psyche </em>will be the first time a craft using a Hall-effect thruster has traveled further than the moon (though plenty of spacecraft have used one in Earth orbit). Launched on October 12, <em>Psyche </em>is headed to a stellar body of the same name: a metal-rich asteroid, unique among others made out of stone, and thought to be the core of a planet that never formed.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-chandrayaan-3-by-the-indian-space-research-organisation-isro-the-first-craft-to-land-at-the-lunar-south-pole">Chandrayaan-3 by the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO): The first craft to land at the lunar south pole</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.isro.gov.in/Chandrayaan3.html" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Chandrayaan-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>ISRO</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.isro.gov.in/Chandrayaan3.html"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Before this year, no one had ever landed in the moon’s south polar region (a region where water ice is plentiful), not even with an uncrewed craft. On August 23, the ISRO changed that when the lander of its latest lunar mission, Chandrayaan-3 (from Sanskrit words meaning “moon craft three”), touched down. In the days that followed, that lander (<em>Vikram)</em> and its attached rover (<em>Pragyan)</em> conducted the first-ever scientific tests of the south polar surface. Unfortunately, a month after its landing, both the lander and rover failed to respond to a wake-up call. Still, Chandrayaan-3 undeniably helped break new ground. There is a good reason that NASA plans to someday land astronauts near the South Pole: The water ice could perhaps support human habitation.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-the-b-21-raider-by-northrop-grumman-a-stealth-bomber-for-the-21st-century">The B-21 Raider by Northrop Grumman: A stealth bomber for the 21st century</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.northropgrumman.com/what-we-do/air/b-21-raider" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/B-21-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Northrop Grumman</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.northropgrumman.com/what-we-do/air/b-21-raider"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Way back in 1988, the US Air Force unveiled the B-2 Spirit, the first stealth bomber in its arsenal. That futuristic aircraft, a flying wing, earned a Best of What’s New award from PopSci that year. More than three decades later, Northrop Grumman <a href="https://www.popsci.com/technology/b-21-raider-bomber-reveal/">rolled out</a> that aircraft’s successor, a sixth-generation flying machine intended to eventually replace the B-2, which the Air Force only owns a relatively small number of. The B-21 Raider is designed to be able to evade detection by radar and will have the capability to deploy either conventional or nuclear weapons. As of November 10, it is in flight testing.</p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading has-text-align-center" id="emergency-service-defense" style="font-style:normal;font-weight:700">Emergency Service and Defense</h2>



<p>As technology evolves and iterates, so does war. Breakthroughs in materials science allow for better body armor, hopefully saving lives. An expanded definition of service means providing appropriate clothing for all soldiers, regardless of anatomy. The cheap and widespread availability of quadcopters has changed how squads scout and fight, as hobbyist toys are turned by the tens of thousands into short-range eyes in the sky. And the climate is warming, which means militaries are turning to new ways to ensure the electrical power stays on despite grid failures. This year’s best emergency services and defense innovations meet the world where it is, and offer added protection and redundancy so that more people can live to see tomorrow.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-grand-award-winner-emergency-service-and-defense">Grand Award Winner, Emergency Service and Defense </h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-kevlar-exo-by-dupont-lighter-body-armor">Kevlar EXO by Dupont: Lighter body armor</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.dupont.com/life-protection/kevlar-exo.html" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Kevlar-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Dupont</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.dupont.com/life-protection/kevlar-exo.html"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>On April 14, DuPont announced <a href="https://www.popsci.com/technology/new-kevlar-exo-body-armor/">Kevlar EXO</a>, a new variant on Kevlar that incorporates a third monomer molecule into its fibrous composition. That change makes the new fiber as strong as existing Kevlar but at lighter weights: existing Kevlar weighs 1 pound per square foot, while Kevlar EXO is between 0.65 and 0.7 pounds per square foot. That’s an improvement of over 30 percent, ensuring that the new material can overcome one of the biggest obstacles to ensuring body armor offers protection: the lighter the body armor, the easier it is for a person to wear it. The hope is that Kevlar EXO will be able to meet body armor standards with a thinner layer, letting the armor go from the lab and into the field, where it can save lives.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-army-tactical-bra-by-u-s-army-combat-capabilities-development-command-at-last-a-durable-undergarment-for-all-bodies-in-the-military">Army Tactical Bra by U.S. Army Combat Capabilities Development Command: At last, a durable undergarment for all bodies in the military</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.army.mil/article/259756/devcom_scs_army_tactical_bras_designed_to_meet_the_performance_needs_of_female_soldiers" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Army-Tactical-Brassiere-FNL-.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>U.S. Army Combat Capabilities Development Command</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.army.mil/article/259756/devcom_scs_army_tactical_bras_designed_to_meet_the_performance_needs_of_female_soldiers"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>The Army Tactical Brassiere, which is currently in its prototype phase, is the first bra designed specifically by the U.S. Army to be worn into ground combat. Created by U.S. Army Combat Capabilities Development Command Soldier Center, or DEVCOM SC, the stain-concealing black bra prototype is flame-resistant and may have a redundant closure mechanism to endure long deployments. Women make up 17 percent of the active-duty US military and must buy their own support, often layering sports bras. Four Army Tactical Bra variants are designed to fit more bodies, and can work with uniforms, armor, and tactical gear, ensuring the services remain open to anyone capable of the job.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-rq-28a-short-range-reconnaissance-system-by-skydio-a-us-quadcopter-for-squads-and-scouts">RQ-28A, Short Range Reconnaissance System by Skydio: A US quadcopter for squads and scouts</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.army.mil/article/261063/new_short_range_reconnaissance_capability_begins_fielding_to_soldiers" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Skydio-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Skydio</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.army.mil/article/261063/new_short_range_reconnaissance_capability_begins_fielding_to_soldiers"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Made by Skydio, the RQ-28A drone is the Army’s first “program of record” quadcopter, which means it has gone from idea to a regular part of the Army’s budget and planning. This ends years in which the US Army struggled to find a quadcopter that works in the field, but didn’t have the risks associated with being an off-the-shelf toy pressed into military use. In November 2022, the 75th Ranger Regiment at Fort Benning, Georgia, successfully fielded the RQ-28A. Weighing less than five pounds, it can be carried in a rucksack and quickly deployed. The drone is controlled from an Army handset, and has a camera that shares video in visual and infrared light.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-oklo-micro-reactor-by-oklo-inc-resilient-backup-power-no-fossil-fuels-needed">Oklo Micro Reactor by Oklo Inc: Resilient backup power, no fossil fuels needed</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://oklo.com/technology/default.aspx" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Oklo-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
          <figcaption class="ProductCardSimple-contentDescription">
        <p><em>Oklo Inc</em></p>

      </figcaption>
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://oklo.com/technology/default.aspx"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>In August 2023, the Air Force announced the award of a contract to California-based Oklo to design and construct, and then own and operate, a micro nuclear reactor at Eielson Air Force Base in Alaska. The reactor, intended to go online in 2027, is aiming to provide 5 megawatts of power. That’s less than one sixth of the electricity already provided by Eielson’s coal and oil power plant, but it’s still a good basis for ensuring that emergency functions can continue if the base otherwise loses power. Should the reactor prove successful, power generators like this could become a tool for resiliency in both military and civil grids.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-barracuda-ultra-lightweight-camouflage-screen-with-frequency-selective-surface-technology-by-saab-camouflage-that-s-communication-friendly">Barracuda Ultra-lightweight Camouflage Screen with Frequency Selective Surface technology by Saab: Camouflage that’s communication-friendly</h3>


<div
    class="ProductCardSimple"
  data-id="ProductCardSimple"
>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-image">
                          <a target="_blank" href="https://www.saab.com/products/ulcas" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">
                    <figure class="wp-block-image size-large">
            <img decoding="async" src="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" srcset="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=330&crop=16:10,offset-x50 330w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=360&crop=16:10,offset-x50 360w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=382&crop=16:10,offset-x50 382w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=800&crop=16:10,offset-x50 800w,https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&optimize=high&width=1440&crop=16:10,offset-x50 1440w" data-image="https://www.popsci.com/uploads/2023/11/29/Saab-netting-FNL.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=800&amp;crop=16:10,offset-x50" loading="lazy" width="800" height="500" alt="Best of What's New photo">
                      </figure>
                  </a>
            </div>
  <div class="ProductCardSimple-content">
              <p class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtnWrap">
        <a class="ProductCardSimple-contentBtn btn" href="https://www.saab.com/products/ulcas"
         target="_blank" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer">Learn More</a>
      </p>
      </div>
</div>



<p>Multispectral camouflage netting must hide the people, vehicles, and equipment under it from visual sight, infrared cameras, and detection by radar. But this type of camouflage can block desired radio signals going in and out, leaving those hiding underneath it in the dark when they need to communicate with allies in the field. In August 2023, Saab announced the new frequency Selective Surface technology for its Barracuda Ultra-lightweight Camouflage Screen, which allows certain radio signals to be sent from underneath the netting, while still protecting against detection by radar. That means soldiers hiding under the net are still hidden from foes, but are still in communication with friendly forces.</p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>



